\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
As an extension of the previous version, the context of use is also in a
 therapy session in a sufficiently large room to be shared by the child
 and Teo.
 However, the room must also be equipped with some technology to support
 this game: monitor/projector and RFID-tagged objects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic premise of the game is based on the use of sound guidance that
 is core of the Marcopolo game.
 However, the target to be reach by Teo is different: Teo must be guided
 by the child to pass through different positions in the room following
 a determined sequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this version, the participation of the therapist will be kept as before,
 being an observer of the game and control Teo, in case it is necessary.
 Also, provide the reinforcement and guidance when the child needs it to
 start/continue with the game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of the game is to help the child to associate the sequence presented
 to a spatial relation with physical objects and positions in space, in
 addition to generating a dynamic in which the interaction between the child
 and Teo can become more natural and comfortable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Interface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The therapist selects through the computer application 
